{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      Client-Side State (helper.js owns everything)\n      All annotation state lives in the browser — positions, text, lifecycle status. Stored in localStorage keyed by session ID. The events file only gets written when you return to the terminal (batch send). Claude pushes new HTML, helper.js re-renders persisted annotations on top.\n      \n        \n          Pros\n          \n            Zero server changes — all logic in helper.js\n            Annotations survive page reloads (localStorage)\n            Clean separation: browser owns UI state, events file is just the export format\n            Fast — no round-trip for every note\n          \n        \n        \n          Cons\n          \n            Re-attaching annotations after Claude pushes new HTML requires matching elements across versions (selectors may shift)\n            localStorage is per-origin, so all sessions on localhost share it (need session-keying)","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1775591974214}
